## Escape sequence characters

Escape sequence characters in Python are special combinations of characters that begin with a backslash (`\`) and 
represent certain whitespace, formatting, or control characters.
They're used inside strings to insert things like new lines, tabs, or special symbols.

| Escape Sequence | Meaning                          | Example Output               |
|-----------------|----------------------------------|------------------------------|
| `\n`            | New line                         | `"Hello\nWorld"` â†’ Hello<br>World |
| `\t`            | Horizontal tab                   | `"Hello\tWorld"` â†’ Hello   â€ƒWorld |
| `\\`            | Backslash                        | `"C:\\Users"` â†’ C:\Users     |
| `\'`            | Single quote                     | `'It\'s fine'` â†’ It's fine   |
| `\"`            | Double quote                     | `"She said \"Hi\""` â†’ She said "Hi" |
| `\r`            | Carriage return                  | `"Hello\rWorld"` â†’ World     |
| `\b`            | Backspace                        | `"Hell\blo"` â†’ Helo          |
| `\f`            | Form feed                        | `"Hello\fWorld"` â†’ HelloWorld |
| `\a`            | Bell (alert sound)               | `"Hello\a"` â†’ (may beep)     |
| `\v`            | Vertical tab                     | `"Hello\vWorld"` â†’ HelloWorld |
| `\ooo`          | Octal value                      | `"\101"` â†’ A                 |
| `\xhh`          | Hexadecimal value                | `"\x41"` â†’ A                 |

